codex
The new projection bindings accept inconsistent flat specs and silently lose caller-supplied sub-field data. This should be fixed so accepted projection declarations round-trip or fail explicitly.

Full review comments:

- [P2] Reject orphaned Python projection sub-fields — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/orch-0.8.20-s15b/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-py/src/lib.rs:903-906
  When a Python caller passes `ProjectionSpec(fts=False, fts_tokenizer="x")` or `vector=False, vector_embedder="x"`, this conversion accepts the request but silently drops the tokenizer/embedder because the Rust sub-object is only built when the boolean is true. That makes `configure_projections` report success while `read.projections` cannot round-trip what the caller supplied; the binding should reject these inconsistent flat shapes before applying the registry change.

- [P2] Reject orphaned TypeScript projection sub-fields — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/orch-0.8.20-s15b/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-napi/src/lib.rs:518-521
  When a TypeScript caller sends `{ fts: false, ftsTokenizer: "x" }` or `{ vector: false, vectorEmbedder: "x" }`, this conversion accepts the object but silently discards the supplied tokenizer/embedder because the Rust sub-object is only constructed when the boolean is true. That means `configureProjections` succeeds while `read.projections` returns a different spec, so the napi boundary should reject these inconsistent flat shapes.
